# Absolute Positioning ðŸ“Œ

Removed from normal flow (no gap left behind).

Positioned relative to the nearest **positioned ancestor** (an ancestor with `relative`, `absolute`, or `fixed` - not `static`).

```css
.container { position: relative; }
.child {
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
}
```
This places `.child` in the top-right corner of `.container`. If no ancestor is positioned, it relates to the body.

# Fixed & Sticky ðŸ“Œ

## Fixed
Positioned relative to the **viewport** (browser window). It stays there when you scroll!
```css
.navbar {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  width: 100%;
}
```

## Sticky
Toggles between relative and fixed depending on scroll position.
```css
.header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
}
```
Acts normal until you scroll to it, then it "sticks" to the top.

# Z-Index (Stack Order) ðŸ“š

When elements overlap, `z-index` decides which one is on top.

- Must have a `position` (anything but static).
- Higher number = on top.

```css
.img { 
  position: absolute;
  z-index: -1; /* Behind text */
}
.text {
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1; /* In front */
}
```
